In experiment, the entire tomography process for a PPS becomes: given measurements $\mbox{Tr}(\rho\sigma_{k})= \epsilon\mbox{Tr}(\rho_{t}\sigma_{k})=M_{k}$, find a density matrix $\rho_{rec}$ to best fit the data $M_k$. In order to evaluate the performance of our protocol, two comparisons will be made. First, we compare the reconstructed state using the optimum number of Pauli measurements with the one obtained with full tomography. It gives us an idea how good the reconstruction is, and whether the protocol works. Second, we compare our result with the state reconstructed by randomly choosing Pauli measurements. This tells us how different the performance is between selecting the optimum set and a random set of Pauli measurements.

